WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:39.660 --> 00:00:46.540
﻿Nikola, the handball world agrees that
you are one of the best, and for some,

00:00:46.780 --> 00:00:50.529
the best handball player
of the modern era.

00:00:50.980 --> 00:00:56.178
Simply, the number of trophies,
both club and national team,

00:00:56.356 --> 00:01:00.403
and when you add individual
awards and, above all,

00:01:00.598 --> 00:01:05.532
the duration of your career,
the many years you played

00:01:05.820 --> 00:01:10.060
at the highest level, it truly places
you on the pedestal of handball legends.

00:01:10.780 --> 00:01:14.300
How do you feel now in your
first season when there are no more

00:01:14.500 --> 00:01:19.100
big responsibilities you were
so used to? -I feel great.

00:01:19.820 --> 00:01:24.180
For the first time, I live without that
inner feeling of needing to be

00:01:24.420 --> 00:01:28.700
the best on the court, in handball.

00:01:29.900 --> 00:01:33.740
There is no longer
that sport and motivation.

00:01:34.340 --> 00:01:40.517
Every day, I’m learning how to live
without the pressure of having

00:01:40.853 --> 00:01:44.235
to win games and win titles.

00:01:45.420 --> 00:01:52.180
I’m slowly getting used to
normal life. It’s nice. I enjoy it.

00:01:52.420 --> 00:01:55.140
I spend more time with my family.

00:01:55.380 --> 00:02:00.980
I have more time for my wife,
for my children, for friends.

00:02:01.780 --> 00:02:05.620
I’m learning how to use
all the knowledge

00:02:05.940 --> 00:02:09.940
I gained through sports
and throughout my career,

00:02:10.180 --> 00:02:15.460
not only in professional sports
but also in working with children,

00:02:16.020 --> 00:02:19.340
the media, and companies.

00:02:20.060 --> 00:02:28.420
I am adapting to my new life
and new rules. -Bravo.

00:02:29.020 --> 00:02:31.460
Thank you for hosting us here in Paris.

00:02:34.180 --> 00:02:38.684
Many players, when they finish their
careers as professional handball players,

00:02:38.913 --> 00:02:41.793
immediately start working
as directors or coaches in the sport.

00:02:42.048 --> 00:02:46.246
Others take a long break, but you’ve
said that you don’t miss handball.

00:02:47.193 --> 00:02:48.513
That’s good.

00:02:48.716 --> 00:02:52.332
However, it would be a shame
for you and for handball if,

00:02:52.502 --> 00:02:55.782
in the near future,
you don’t return to it.

00:02:56.023 --> 00:03:02.905
Because athletes and children
need their childhood idols

00:03:03.218 --> 00:03:07.132
to still be present in the sport.

00:03:09.660 --> 00:03:15.034
I don't feel like I don't miss handball,
but I don't miss the competition.

00:03:15.780 --> 00:03:21.620
You know how it is, that athlete
mentality pushes you to be the best

00:03:21.900 --> 00:03:24.660
and to give everything you’ve got.

00:03:25.620 --> 00:03:33.260
To be better than the person opposite you.
And better than all the other teams.

00:03:33.540 --> 00:03:35.500
I don’t miss that mentality.

00:03:35.700 --> 00:03:39.220
That feeling that I’m only happy
when I win and when I win a medal.

00:03:39.303 --> 00:03:40.903
I don’t miss that.

00:03:41.128 --> 00:03:51.088
I always followed the desire to be
the best and to have the best career.

00:03:51.820 --> 00:03:54.900
But I don’t miss that anymore.

00:03:55.126 --> 00:03:59.326
I don’t miss sport and handball because
I watch handball games every day.

00:03:59.474 --> 00:04:02.674
I’m still an ambassador
for Paris Saint-Germain,

00:04:02.805 --> 00:04:04.725
my son also plays handball.

00:04:04.902 --> 00:04:08.062
I come to the games,
and I watch handball on TV.

00:04:08.310 --> 00:04:11.919
I have a contract with beIN Sports,
which is a French TV channel

00:04:12.049 --> 00:04:14.301
that broadcasts handball matches.

00:04:14.418 --> 00:04:16.988
At beIN Sports, I participate
as an expert commentator.

00:04:17.085 --> 00:04:19.731
I don’t miss handball,
because I never really left it.

00:04:19.887 --> 00:04:23.245
Together with my brother,
I founded a handball academy.

00:04:24.781 --> 00:04:31.261
Your time is filled. -What I don't
miss is professional handball.

00:04:31.900 --> 00:04:37.020
I know that I could probably be
a good coach, because I had

00:04:37.299 --> 00:04:41.480
the opportunity to learn a lot from
the coaches who trained me.

00:04:41.737 --> 00:04:47.457
I know that I could be a good coach.
But being a coach is very hard.

00:04:47.805 --> 00:04:50.765
My professional career
lasted almost 24 years.

00:04:51.083 --> 00:04:56.042
So I needed a break from
playing sports professionally.

00:04:56.197 --> 00:04:59.957
I understand. Because it’s not easy...
It’s like some kind of "hangover".

00:05:00.304 --> 00:05:03.784
You actually live your whole
life on a sports schedule.

00:05:04.149 --> 00:05:07.669
It’s not just about training,
adrenaline, and matches.

00:05:07.830 --> 00:05:11.925
You also have to think about
nutrition, rest, sleep, waking up.

00:05:12.061 --> 00:05:14.421
And respecting all of that is not easy.

00:05:14.589 --> 00:05:18.120
I’m sure that later you’ll get
back into handball even more.

00:05:18.291 --> 00:05:23.291
But let’s go back to the period
of your life when you were in Niš.

00:05:23.429 --> 00:05:29.349
You were born in Niš in 1984,
your father Branko is Croatian

00:05:29.479 --> 00:05:31.722
from the area around Trogir.

00:05:31.934 --> 00:05:38.269
He was a handball goalkeeper and signed
a contract with RK Mehanika from Niš.

00:05:38.784 --> 00:05:44.944
There he met your mother Radmila,
who was finishing her medical studies,

00:05:45.820 --> 00:05:49.860
when you were 3.5 years old,
and after that, you moved to Paris.

00:05:49.965 --> 00:05:52.861
Do you remember that period
when you lived in Niš,

00:05:52.958 --> 00:05:55.096
or were you simply
too young to recall it?

00:05:56.100 --> 00:05:59.500
I was too young to remember anything.

00:06:00.700 --> 00:06:05.980
I remember some fragments,
but I’m not sure if those memories

00:06:06.340 --> 00:06:13.340
are related to Niš or to a place
near Trogir, where my father is from.

00:06:13.580 --> 00:06:19.540
I remember some...
-Fragments. -Yes, fragments.

00:06:19.820 --> 00:06:24.980
But I don’t remember everything,
because we traveled a lot.

00:06:25.180 --> 00:06:28.900
We would go to Niš,
where part of our family was,

00:06:29.140 --> 00:06:34.700
then to Trogir, Strasbourg, Colmar.

00:06:35.700 --> 00:06:43.300
After that, we moved to Montpellier.
We traveled a lot and changed locations.

00:06:44.460 --> 00:06:47.980
I remember a lot of things,
but I don’t know which year

00:06:48.180 --> 00:06:50.620
it was and when exactly
something happened.

00:06:50.860 --> 00:06:54.060
The only thing I remember is that
I was always with my family,

00:06:54.260 --> 00:06:56.460
my father, my mother,
and my brother Luka.

00:06:56.700 --> 00:06:59.020
We were very close to each other.

00:06:59.260 --> 00:07:02.900
That meant a lot to me
and helped me a lot. -Yes.

00:07:03.100 --> 00:07:08.860
We loved each other a lot.
-You know that, I’ll help you...

00:07:09.700 --> 00:07:15.900
I want to give you an idea of how good
the sport was in the former Yugoslavia.

00:07:16.147 --> 00:07:19.227
You were born in April 1984.

00:07:19.474 --> 00:07:22.925
Did you know that in December 1983,
a football match was played in Niš

00:07:23.079 --> 00:07:26.574
between Radnički and Hajduk?
But it was a UEFA Cup match,

00:07:26.789 --> 00:07:32.090
which is the same as today’s Europa League.
It was the round of 16, the third round.

00:07:32.289 --> 00:07:35.238
Dragan Stojković Piksi was playing
for Radnički at that time.

00:07:35.411 --> 00:07:37.891
However, Hajduk won 2:0 in Niš.

00:07:38.030 --> 00:07:40.746
The goals were scored by
Zlatko Vujović and Zoran Vulić.

00:07:40.891 --> 00:07:44.965
Then in Split, the result was again
2:0, with Zlatko Vujović scoring.

00:07:45.602 --> 00:07:48.242
I remember that, and that was
around the time you were born.

00:07:48.513 --> 00:07:53.673
How was your growing up in Strasbourg?
You came there at 3.5 years old.

00:07:54.340 --> 00:07:58.353
How was it for you, growing up
as a foreigner in France?

00:08:02.380 --> 00:08:08.340
I never felt like a foreigner.
I know my father and mother...

00:08:08.620 --> 00:08:11.540
My father always said that
it was very important for us to

00:08:11.740 --> 00:08:14.540
integrate into French society.

00:08:15.260 --> 00:08:17.860
That we had to learn
the French language.

00:08:18.140 --> 00:08:22.900
We were always very
proud of our roots.

00:08:23.100 --> 00:08:25.700
Of the former Yugoslavia,
Croatia, and Serbia.

00:08:25.940 --> 00:08:27.860
All those countries are ours.

00:08:28.100 --> 00:08:30.500
But at the same time,
my father was proud

00:08:30.700 --> 00:08:33.300
when we got French citizenship.

00:08:34.140 --> 00:08:39.740
And when we became part
of the great French nation.

00:08:42.100 --> 00:08:44.980
I never felt like a foreigner.

00:08:45.380 --> 00:08:50.660
I always felt like a Frenchman.
Half French, half Yugoslav.

00:08:51.340 --> 00:08:57.420
I think that helped me a lot
and broadened my horizons.

00:09:02.140 --> 00:09:09.980
So I always respected all nations
and those who were different from me.

00:09:11.020 --> 00:09:15.820
That gave us strength,
and I never felt like a foreigner.

00:09:16.700 --> 00:09:19.346
You came to France at 3.5
years old, and your father got a job

00:09:19.413 --> 00:09:20.973
as a handball coach, right?

00:09:21.096 --> 00:09:22.376
That’s right.

00:09:22.499 --> 00:09:26.854
In Strasbourg, and of course, you
started playing handball right away.

00:09:28.820 --> 00:09:35.692
You often say that your father is
the most important person in your life.

00:09:36.540 --> 00:09:39.340
Your mother says that
your father was always

00:09:39.447 --> 00:09:42.130
an advocate of order,
hard work, and discipline.

00:09:42.278 --> 00:09:44.118
He was strict and fair.

00:09:44.691 --> 00:09:47.653
It’s clear that you also fell
in love with handball.

00:09:47.699 --> 00:09:49.459
How do you remember him?

00:09:50.860 --> 00:10:00.420
I remember him as the best role model,
and at the same time, he was my father.

00:10:01.860 --> 00:10:05.500
Later, when we moved from
Strasbourg to Frontignan,

00:10:05.780 --> 00:10:11.260
a town near Montpellier,
he became my sports teacher

00:10:11.500 --> 00:10:14.340
in school and my handball coach.

00:10:14.620 --> 00:10:19.060
So I couldn’t have had
a better role model than him.

00:10:19.380 --> 00:10:22.500
As you said, he was from
the "old school" and believed

00:10:22.740 --> 00:10:25.660
that everything could be
achieved if you worked,

00:10:25.980 --> 00:10:29.420
if you behaved well
on the court and at school,

00:10:29.620 --> 00:10:34.540
if you respected coaches,
referees, and opponents.

00:10:34.780 --> 00:10:43.140
At the same time, he was a philosopher
of life and had a positive energy.

00:10:43.860 --> 00:10:50.540
My father taught me discipline,
but at the same time,

00:10:50.820 --> 00:10:54.980
he taught me to enjoy life.
Because life is beautiful.

00:10:55.180 --> 00:11:01.060
And from my mother, I inherited
that inner fire, which I notice

00:11:01.300 --> 00:11:05.980
in other athletes from
the former Yugoslavia.

00:11:06.220 --> 00:11:09.900
That drives them to be the best
and to achieve great results.

00:11:10.180 --> 00:11:14.700
I couldn’t have had a better combination
than my father and mother.

00:11:14.940 --> 00:11:22.060
And growing up in France
really broadened my horizons.

00:11:22.174 --> 00:11:24.974
I had the opportunity
to see other cultures.

00:11:25.105 --> 00:11:27.385
I had that double strength.

00:11:27.521 --> 00:11:30.421
I believe I couldn’t have had
a better family than mine. -Yes.

00:11:30.980 --> 00:11:34.980
Mom always says
that handball was everything.

00:11:35.260 --> 00:11:38.180
You woke up and went to sleep
with it on your mind.

00:11:38.500 --> 00:11:43.380
You had a solid platform.
Your dad was your coach,

00:11:44.020 --> 00:11:47.100
then after your training sessions,
you'd watch your dad train,

00:11:47.340 --> 00:11:51.140
then you would also train at home,
watch video tapes, compare yourself,

00:11:51.380 --> 00:11:53.500
and even ask your dad:
"Am I better than this?"

00:11:53.700 --> 00:11:58.016
You were always setting goals.
It was always just handball, handball...

00:11:59.462 --> 00:12:06.072
Were the boys you hung out with
also into handball?

00:12:07.178 --> 00:12:10.149
Yes, a lot of them played handball,

00:12:10.304 --> 00:12:12.962
or they joined because
they were my friends.

00:12:13.169 --> 00:12:17.453
Because my dad was a coach,
I'm convinced that if my dad

00:12:18.046 --> 00:12:27.166
had been a basketball or football coach,
I would've followed that sport.

00:12:27.663 --> 00:12:30.881
I understand that...
-I know that a lot...

00:12:31.326 --> 00:12:36.886
A big part of what I've done in my
career is because of my family

00:12:37.220 --> 00:12:41.900
and wanting my dad to be proud of me...
-To prove yourself to him, right?

00:12:42.140 --> 00:12:47.660
Exactly, to prove myself to him, to
prove that maybe I was better than him.

00:12:47.900 --> 00:12:52.207
You're always looking for your parents'
love, even though they're showing it.

00:12:52.502 --> 00:12:57.207
But I think that gave me
a lot of motivation.

00:12:58.196 --> 00:13:01.949
I did everything for him,
for my mom, for my brother,

00:13:02.310 --> 00:13:06.527
and of course, I was lucky enough to
have my younger brother by my side.

00:13:06.887 --> 00:13:13.230
We played handball together, tennis,
all sorts of sports at home after practice.

00:13:13.543 --> 00:13:18.589
I honestly couldn't have had
a better childhood.

00:13:18.900 --> 00:13:23.540
I also witnessed how my mom
and dad gave us everything.

00:13:23.780 --> 00:13:27.140
My dad played in the former Yugoslavia,
he was a national team player.

00:13:27.380 --> 00:13:31.500
And my mom got her degree to be a
doctor, but when they came to France,

00:13:31.670 --> 00:13:34.447
their achievements
weren't recognized there...

00:13:34.618 --> 00:13:36.458
My dad coached in the second league,

00:13:36.604 --> 00:13:38.994
and later he worked in Frantignan
for the fourth or fifth division.

00:13:39.247 --> 00:13:42.963
And my mom couldn't be a doctor because
they didn't recognize her diplomas.

00:13:43.420 --> 00:13:47.460
I saw how they gave everything they had,

00:13:48.140 --> 00:13:53.940
how their professional lives
were so different

00:13:54.196 --> 00:13:56.676
from what they had back in
the former Yugoslavia.

00:13:56.783 --> 00:13:58.877
They did all of that for the family.

00:13:59.190 --> 00:14:01.838
It wasn't just a sacrifice,
it was everything they gave for us.

00:14:01.971 --> 00:14:04.091
But it's a sacrifice for you...

00:14:04.316 --> 00:14:07.783
That really had an influence on me,
to give something back to them.

00:14:08.379 --> 00:14:14.041
And throughout my career,
that has been a big motivation.

00:14:15.060 --> 00:14:20.540
Yes, and it's really interesting.
Mom says exactly that.

00:14:20.820 --> 00:14:26.220
Handball was important, but so were
work habits and responsibilities.

00:14:26.460 --> 00:14:30.820
Of course, handball matters,
but school had to be taken care of too,

00:14:31.060 --> 00:14:33.780
possibly with more difficulty there...

00:14:34.020 --> 00:14:40.340
You, as a kid, learned French
faster than your mom and dad. -Yes.

00:14:40.580 --> 00:14:43.180
Because little kids are like sponges.

00:14:43.340 --> 00:14:48.420
They told you and Luka:
"We can't help you with school anymore.

00:14:48.660 --> 00:14:52.820
You have to do it on your own." That
gave you responsibility, obligations,

00:14:53.020 --> 00:14:56.340
and work habits that would later
help you in handball.

00:14:56.580 --> 00:15:04.260
Exactly. Like you said, we spoke French
faster and better than our parents.

00:15:05.340 --> 00:15:09.220
We did our homework
on our own at home.

00:15:10.980 --> 00:15:15.420
School was like a competition for us.
We wanted to be the best in school,

00:15:15.860 --> 00:15:18.780
and in our class...
We always had the best grades.

00:15:22.420 --> 00:15:26.860
It mattered to us to be the best,
not only in sport but also in school,

00:15:27.260 --> 00:15:32.100
because that's where we showed
our family that we succeeded.

00:15:33.100 --> 00:15:39.460
Something our parents passed on to us
was to always be the best, everywhere.

00:15:40.660 --> 00:15:44.340
We always wanted to compare
ourselves with others

00:15:44.540 --> 00:15:47.340
and show that we were better than them.

00:15:47.740 --> 00:15:52.620
I remember when my dad would
tell me about his career,

00:15:52.860 --> 00:15:55.620
how he played in Metković
for a long time.

00:15:56.020 --> 00:16:02.140
At the time, we were watching Croatia
win the Olympic Games in 1996.

00:16:02.580 --> 00:16:05.500
Patrik Čavar was playing,
and he was my idol.

00:16:05.700 --> 00:16:10.380
My dad always told me when he played
in Metković, Patrik was a kid there.

00:16:10.780 --> 00:16:18.124
I'd always ask: "Dad, am I better than
Patrik when he was my age?"

00:16:19.020 --> 00:16:22.540
And he'd say: "Okay, he was good,
you're not bad either,

00:16:22.740 --> 00:16:26.740
but you have to train a lot
to catch up to him."

00:16:26.980 --> 00:16:34.050
I always had that competitive mindset,
comparing myself to everyone,

00:16:34.589 --> 00:16:42.181
always having to be better than
other kids in school, in handball...

00:16:44.100 --> 00:16:46.500
Did other sports interest you?

00:16:46.860 --> 00:16:51.700
I mean, this was the early '90s, right?

00:16:54.740 --> 00:16:59.747
In France, football was big, basketball
not so much, rugby was present too,

00:16:59.819 --> 00:17:01.997
and there were individual sports too.

00:17:02.780 --> 00:17:06.740
For example, in Marseille,
you had Piksi Stojković, Bokšić,

00:17:08.500 --> 00:17:12.060
and Zidane, Cantona,
Ginola are there.

00:17:12.300 --> 00:17:16.180
And you had posters of
Jackson Richardson on your wall.

00:17:16.420 --> 00:17:19.900
Yes, I had Jackson Richardson's poster.

00:17:20.220 --> 00:17:25.460
I had posters of a lot of players
from the former Yugoslavia.

00:17:25.940 --> 00:17:28.380
I know I had a poster
of Croatian players like

00:17:28.580 --> 00:17:34.060
Čavar, Nenad Peruničić,
Jovanović, Skrivić.

00:17:35.820 --> 00:17:40.900
We talked a lot about handball at home.
We always used to follow dad,

00:17:41.140 --> 00:17:50.060
and go to some games where legends from
the former Yugoslavia or France played.

00:17:50.300 --> 00:17:53.220
Dad would talk to them,
and we'd see all of that...

00:17:53.780 --> 00:17:56.620
And that just added to everything.
-Of course, of course.

00:17:56.900 --> 00:18:02.100
My dad was a role model,
and Luka and I wanted to impress him.

00:18:04.020 --> 00:18:07.260
I remember when
we were living there,

00:18:07.500 --> 00:18:11.500
I'm not sure which part of Strasbourg it
was, but Piksi had his surgery there,

00:18:11.660 --> 00:18:13.580
and we went to see him.

00:18:13.820 --> 00:18:18.260
I remember Luka crawling under
the bed, and the bed fell over...

00:18:18.860 --> 00:18:23.020
We were worried it might
mess up his surgery.

00:18:23.300 --> 00:18:28.100
So those stories were always there,
and dad always talked with great pride

00:18:29.860 --> 00:18:33.300
about the former Yugoslavia
and all those athletes.

00:18:33.540 --> 00:18:37.580
Handball was a real sport there,
it was respected.

00:18:37.780 --> 00:18:40.940
But in France at the time,
handball wasn't that big.

00:18:41.180 --> 00:18:44.660
It was hard for me as a kid
to follow those games,

00:18:44.900 --> 00:18:48.060
watch Jackson and the clubs I loved.

00:18:48.420 --> 00:18:54.060
But I knew, and it was also motivation
for me to make handball a big sport

00:18:54.460 --> 00:18:58.740
in France through my career,
not just football and the other sports.

00:18:58.980 --> 00:19:03.740
I wanted people in France
to respect handball

00:19:03.940 --> 00:19:06.980
the way it was respected
in the former Yugoslavia.

00:19:09.140 --> 00:19:13.180
That dedication you had from the start,
as your mom said...

00:19:14.780 --> 00:19:20.100
You trained all day,
always thinking about handball.

00:19:21.220 --> 00:19:25.340
Dad didn't want you to go to the gym
when you were going through puberty

00:19:25.540 --> 00:19:28.380
because it was too early for your body.

00:19:28.580 --> 00:19:36.380
So, you made your own little imitation
gym in your room with a weight machine.

00:19:36.820 --> 00:19:38.140
Yes.

00:19:42.580 --> 00:19:45.420
And then you moved
to Montpellier. Why?

00:19:45.700 --> 00:19:48.420
Was it because it was
a good handball environment,

00:19:48.660 --> 00:19:52.860
or was it because the climate
was better than in Strasbourg?

00:19:53.260 --> 00:19:57.420
I always thought it was a decision
made by both mom and dad,

00:19:57.660 --> 00:20:02.260
but mom explained to me that she
actually wanted to move to Montpellier.

00:20:02.900 --> 00:20:06.660
We were in Strasbourg where my dad
was playing and coaching.

00:20:07.020 --> 00:20:13.580
It was the second league, and they were
fighting to move up to the first league.

00:20:14.300 --> 00:20:22.020
Then we moved to Kolbsheim,
a town about 20-30 km from Strasbourg,

00:20:22.260 --> 00:20:24.380
and we lived there for two years.

00:20:24.660 --> 00:20:30.060
After that, dad thought about
returning either to Trogir or Niš,

00:20:30.380 --> 00:20:33.820
but mom wanted to stay in France.

00:20:35.100 --> 00:20:40.340
She didn't want to live in Alsace
anymore, she wanted sun, the sea,

00:20:40.580 --> 00:20:45.500
and somehow they found
that club near Montpellier.

00:20:45.780 --> 00:20:51.580
They were playing in the fifth division,
but I think through some connections,

00:20:51.980 --> 00:20:55.580
someone knew the president of the club.

00:20:56.060 --> 00:21:02.068
The president found my dad
a job as a coach in a school.

00:21:02.443 --> 00:21:07.803
So, we moved down there,
and at first, mom didn't work,

00:21:08.045 --> 00:21:12.881
but later she found a job
in a retirement home as a nurse,

00:21:13.220 --> 00:21:15.380
and that's where we stayed.

00:21:16.180 --> 00:21:21.220
We lived there, and mom
still lives near Montpellier.

00:21:22.540 --> 00:21:25.060
I have a house there,
and so does Luka.

00:21:25.300 --> 00:21:31.900
That's where we played,
and we still feel like it's home.

00:21:33.380 --> 00:21:37.060
We had those summers by the sea...

00:21:37.300 --> 00:21:40.740
I'm curious about
your thoughts on something,

00:21:41.180 --> 00:21:44.288
not just from your example,
but also in general.

00:21:44.658 --> 00:21:47.138
Your father was
a handball player, right?

00:21:47.486 --> 00:21:52.326
Often, the children of elite athletes
follow in their footsteps,

00:21:52.820 --> 00:21:59.260
but many break under the pressure
of living up to the family name

00:21:59.460 --> 00:22:03.291
or the stories surrounding them.
There are prejudices, and people say:

00:22:03.541 --> 00:22:07.744
"He's here because of his father."
Did you ever feel that? Or not?

00:22:08.287 --> 00:22:11.550
Was it hard carrying
the name Karabatić?

00:22:13.060 --> 00:22:15.540
It wasn't hard for me.

00:22:16.020 --> 00:22:24.592
It was an honor because I saw how
the handball players in France

00:22:24.975 --> 00:22:31.020
looked up to my dad
and how they respected him.

00:22:31.340 --> 00:22:34.700
That brought me a lot of motivation.

00:22:35.020 --> 00:22:40.480
It wasn't hard because dad
was always there to calm me down,

00:22:40.824 --> 00:22:46.167
even when I was the best. He would tell
me that if I had the ambition

00:22:47.180 --> 00:22:52.980
to become an elite player,
I had to work hard.

00:22:53.500 --> 00:22:58.180
Being the best when I was young
didn't mean I'd stay the best.

00:22:58.460 --> 00:23:02.260
He told me that if I had that dream
and that goal in life,

00:23:02.500 --> 00:23:04.540
the path would be long.

00:23:04.992 --> 00:23:09.192
You can achieve anything in life,
but you have to work for it

00:23:09.511 --> 00:23:13.791
and be strict with yourself.
So, it was never hard for me.

00:23:14.140 --> 00:23:16.180
It was always a motivation.

00:23:16.580 --> 00:23:21.020
I always knew I had a father
who was great,

00:23:21.700 --> 00:23:26.820
and at the same time
coaching 4th or 5th division.

00:23:29.500 --> 00:23:34.220
There’s no ego in our family.
My father played for the national team

00:23:35.980 --> 00:23:41.900
but still wants to coach kids,
or 5th division teams.

00:23:42.380 --> 00:23:47.940
That was a big role model for me.
To see my father is not the type

00:23:48.820 --> 00:23:52.580
who gets arrogant because
he won something in his life.

00:23:52.860 --> 00:23:56.740
He was always kind to everyone,
always gave his best

00:23:56.940 --> 00:24:03.940
to help others, help the kids.
That was a big role model for me.

00:24:04.540 --> 00:24:08.496
I know I have that at home.
To see he’s a big star,

00:24:08.840 --> 00:24:13.060
but still behaves the same
towards everyone.

00:24:13.780 --> 00:24:19.528
That helped me a lot to never
think that I’m,

00:24:20.295 --> 00:24:25.410
even if I’m the best in what I do,
never think I’m the best.

00:24:25.774 --> 00:24:31.254
That I’m better than you in life.
-I asked Ivanišević the same.

00:24:31.620 --> 00:24:35.780
Then your career starts
and lasts over 20 years, right?

00:24:36.340 --> 00:24:42.300
Even if it lasts that long, can you...
Every career has few moments

00:24:42.620 --> 00:24:46.260
that push you forward,
open something for you,

00:24:46.500 --> 00:24:52.660
or sometimes it happens
it holds you back.

00:24:54.950 --> 00:25:01.210
What decisions helped you
that were crucial in your career?

00:25:01.720 --> 00:25:08.194
I remember, I was very lucky
because my career started at 17.

00:25:08.776 --> 00:25:13.741
At 18 I was in the national team,
at 19 I won the Champions League.

00:25:14.199 --> 00:25:19.439
It went brutally upwards.
But, when I look back

00:25:19.860 --> 00:25:23.500
there is one moment, I was
young, maybe 15 years old.

00:25:23.700 --> 00:25:28.060
Until then I was always the best,
in every game I played,

00:25:28.260 --> 00:25:32.700
in every team I played for.
It was some regional selection

00:25:32.940 --> 00:25:38.340
where I played one match.
I missed one or two shots.

00:25:38.580 --> 00:25:42.620
Didn’t play well. We finished
the game, dad was always there.

00:25:42.742 --> 00:25:46.208
Then we talked after the match,
analysed how it was.

00:25:46.434 --> 00:25:51.550
He asked me if I was happy
with the game. I told him I wasn’t.

00:25:52.016 --> 00:25:56.089
Then he asked me if I knew
why he wasn’t happy.

00:25:56.370 --> 00:26:00.310
I said "no, I missed,
didn’t play well."

00:26:00.615 --> 00:26:05.576
He said "no, I’m not happy
because you missed two shots.

00:26:06.167 --> 00:26:09.177
Then you stopped playing,
got scared. Pressure was too big

00:26:09.337 --> 00:26:14.302
so you wouldn’t miss more
and then you stopped."

00:26:15.620 --> 00:26:20.620
If your goal is to be the best in the world
and play for the national team,

00:26:20.900 --> 00:26:27.620
and in a small game, one or two
misses break you down,

00:26:27.860 --> 00:26:34.460
then it’s over, you won’t make it.
Stress will be too big, pressure too.

00:26:34.780 --> 00:26:37.860
Better to quit right now.
Think about it and tomorrow

00:26:38.060 --> 00:26:44.980
tell me what you decided."
That was the first time dad put me...

00:26:45.500 --> 00:26:48.740
On the spot. -Against the wall.

00:26:49.380 --> 00:26:52.220
I had to decide. That was
very important for me,

00:26:52.420 --> 00:26:55.620
because I said then "No, dad,
I want to move forward."

00:26:55.860 --> 00:27:02.660
I told myself "If I don’t succeed,
I’ll be scared on the court."

00:27:04.580 --> 00:27:09.380
My goal was after every game
to give my best on the court.

00:27:09.660 --> 00:27:13.980
To always try and move forward
and if I miss, it’s fine.

00:27:14.220 --> 00:27:20.180
To keep moving forward and never stop.
That really pushed me a lot.

00:27:20.460 --> 00:27:26.980
Actually, that moment was very important
for me, because from that point on

00:27:27.380 --> 00:27:32.020
I was never afraid on the court.
Even though I was 16 or 17 years old,

00:27:32.260 --> 00:27:36.340
I was already playing in the first division
and by 18 I was in the national team.

00:27:36.540 --> 00:27:40.438
I was never afraid to try.
-To take responsibility,

00:27:40.605 --> 00:27:43.352
which marked you throughout
your whole career.

00:27:43.578 --> 00:27:48.477
It's always difficult for young players.
They're always afraid.

00:27:48.801 --> 00:27:54.313
They're playing with players
they had posters of in their rooms.

00:27:54.672 --> 00:27:59.872
Then they get scared. For me, that was
my strength, because I was never afraid.

00:28:00.300 --> 00:28:04.500
I wanted to succeed in that.
That moment was very important to me.

00:28:05.820 --> 00:28:13.700
Incredible. What you mentioned, when you
won the Champions League with Montpellier,

00:28:14.060 --> 00:28:19.540
and in the final, which was played over
two legs, you scored 17 goals. -Yes.

00:28:19.820 --> 00:28:23.020
As a young player,
that really launched you.

00:28:23.300 --> 00:28:27.660
You mentioned that your father
played in Metković. -Yes.

00:28:27.900 --> 00:28:34.740
Was your move to Kiel connected to that,
because Zvonimir Noka Serdarušić,

00:28:35.380 --> 00:28:39.980
a top Croatian coach, was there?
Is there a connection between your father

00:28:40.220 --> 00:28:42.940
and Noka from Metković or not?

00:28:45.020 --> 00:28:49.060
You know how it was
in the former Yugoslavia.

00:28:49.820 --> 00:28:52.340
All athletes were connected.

00:28:52.620 --> 00:28:56.620
My father and Noka didn’t play together
or against each other,

00:28:57.060 --> 00:29:07.660
but they knew each other. Of course,
that influenced my move to the club a lot.

00:29:08.020 --> 00:29:11.140
As well as my decision
to sign for Kiel.

00:29:11.900 --> 00:29:15.460
I was very young then.
I was 20 years old.

00:29:15.700 --> 00:29:22.020
A year before that,
the coach from Pamplona came.

00:29:22.460 --> 00:29:25.060
At that time,
Pamplona was the best team.

00:29:25.300 --> 00:29:28.020
Jackson Richardson played there.
Nedeljko Jovanović too,

00:29:28.220 --> 00:29:31.300
and later Ivano Balić also played there.

00:29:33.060 --> 00:29:39.420
In 2003 we won the Champions League
against... -When you scored 17 goals.

00:29:39.660 --> 00:29:43.920
They called me to join them. My father
and I always talked things through.

00:29:44.143 --> 00:29:48.249
He said OK, of course we’ll hear their
offer, but he thought it was too soon,

00:29:48.544 --> 00:29:54.464
and not the right moment to go there.
I still had a lot to learn in Montpellier.

00:29:54.940 --> 00:30:01.500
When Noka and Kiel called, then I felt
that was the right moment.

00:30:02.220 --> 00:30:07.100
My father always told me that
money isn’t the most important thing.

00:30:07.300 --> 00:30:16.060
Money and contract conditions
shouldn’t be decisive for where I play.

00:30:16.340 --> 00:30:23.324
First I had to look at where I could
develop. Which club was the best

00:30:23.613 --> 00:30:28.140
for my progress and reaching my goal,
to become the best in the world,

00:30:28.340 --> 00:30:31.620
and where I could learn the most.
Money would come later.

00:30:31.860 --> 00:30:34.580
If you’re good, that will come.
That’s secondary.

00:30:34.780 --> 00:30:38.300
I remember when Noka called,
my father said that’s the right club,

00:30:38.460 --> 00:30:43.700
the right coach for me, he can
take me to a higher level. -Yes.

00:30:43.980 --> 00:30:49.460
We made all those decisions together.
My father, mother, Luka.

00:30:49.660 --> 00:30:52.940
We talked a lot. I was young then,
20 years old.

00:30:53.180 --> 00:30:56.100
I didn’t know anything
about life and it’s hard

00:30:56.300 --> 00:30:59.260
if you don’t have
good people around you

00:30:59.460 --> 00:31:02.580
to help you make the right
decisions for your career.

00:31:02.820 --> 00:31:08.500
Was the German league stronger
than the French one back then? -Yes.

00:31:08.860 --> 00:31:12.540
At that time, the Bundesliga
was the strongest in the world.

00:31:13.060 --> 00:31:18.540
There was also the Spanish league,
very strong, with Barcelona, San Antonio,

00:31:18.700 --> 00:31:27.635
Pamplona, Leon, all those big clubs.
But the Bundesliga always...

00:31:28.780 --> 00:31:32.900
I think that’s because
of the respect for handball,

00:31:33.060 --> 00:31:38.700
because in Kiel we had 10,000...
-Fans. -Fans.

00:31:38.980 --> 00:31:43.660
Every game we played in Gummersbach,
in Cologne in front of 20,000 people,

00:31:43.860 --> 00:31:49.020
in Hamburg 14,000. -The atmosphere there.
-The atmosphere was always...

00:31:49.260 --> 00:31:55.940
It was always an honor for me to see those
full arenas, people who love our sport.

00:31:56.180 --> 00:32:01.140
I always wanted to experience that.
That also made a difference.

00:32:01.380 --> 00:32:07.300
Many say you went to Noka
to become the best player in the world.

00:32:07.780 --> 00:32:15.020
That's exactly what happened in the end.
Against Flensburg, you score 16 goals.

00:32:16.740 --> 00:32:21.140
You win your second of three
Champions League titles.

00:32:21.340 --> 00:32:26.180
After that, you return to Montpellier.
Then you briefly go to Aix. -Yes.

00:32:26.420 --> 00:32:31.940
After that, Barcelona, right?
Then you return to Paris.

00:32:32.140 --> 00:32:34.980
With Barcelona, you win
the Champions League.

00:32:35.220 --> 00:32:43.700
You return to Paris, where you continue
your impressive career. Like Jordan.

00:32:44.100 --> 00:32:48.940
That's three Champions League titles
in three different countries. -Yes.

00:32:49.140 --> 00:32:54.980
Sixteen French championships,
four German, two Spanish.

00:32:55.300 --> 00:33:00.020
If I'm not mistaken, only one year
you didn’t win the championship. -Yes.

00:33:00.260 --> 00:33:07.140
That was 2013, right?
-That was the 2012/2013 season.

00:33:07.340 --> 00:33:12.020
That's when the scandal happened.
-That's right. -I left Montpellier then.

00:33:12.220 --> 00:33:19.860
I went to Aix, who were fighting to stay
in the league. Then I moved to Barcelona.

00:33:21.540 --> 00:33:28.300
Barcelona didn’t want to pay a transfer fee.
They said they wanted me,

00:33:28.500 --> 00:33:35.660
but I had to be free. Montpellier wanted to
terminate my contract because of the scandal.

00:33:35.860 --> 00:33:42.500
So I went to Aix. They bought out
my contract for maybe 50,000.

00:33:42.900 --> 00:33:49.660
From Aix I went to Barcelona as a free agent.
That year I didn’t win the championship,

00:33:49.860 --> 00:33:53.060
but we were fighting to stay
in the first league.

00:33:53.260 --> 00:33:58.140
Aix were supposed to be relegated.
We saved the club. Luka played there too.

00:33:58.620 --> 00:34:01.820
Aix are still in the first league.
They have a new arena.

00:34:02.140 --> 00:34:07.340
They played in the European Cup
two years ago. We saved the club,

00:34:07.780 --> 00:34:14.180
and a new dynamic was born. That title
I didn’t win is the only one I’m missing.

00:34:15.820 --> 00:34:19.700
But the emotions were stronger
because we saved the club.

00:34:20.060 --> 00:34:24.620
That club is now one of the best
in France when it comes to handball.

00:34:24.820 --> 00:34:28.700
They have a new arena, they’re a big club,
many fans, and so on.

00:34:28.900 --> 00:34:34.140
Luka and I were there at the beginning
of that story, and it means a lot to us.

00:34:36.340 --> 00:34:41.740
﻿So, a return to Paris is coming,
and a very emotional farewell

00:34:42.740 --> 00:34:48.500
in the arena, in 2024. It’s a shame
your father wasn’t there.

00:34:48.660 --> 00:34:51.140
He left too soon.
Do you miss him?

00:34:53.020 --> 00:35:00.460
Of course I miss him a lot,
but I worked a lot on getting over it.

00:35:03.100 --> 00:35:08.860
It’s always been really hard for me,
because when your father leaves too soon,

00:35:09.180 --> 00:35:11.860
there’s so much you don’t get
to experience with him.

00:35:12.100 --> 00:35:13.980
He didn’t even get to see my children.

00:35:14.220 --> 00:35:17.620
Of course that’s hard,
but I’ve worked a lot on myself

00:35:18.100 --> 00:35:22.660
so that I can feel happy
for having had such a father,

00:35:23.226 --> 00:35:25.017
who gave me so much.

00:35:25.300 --> 00:35:29.340
I realized that he had seen in advance
what was going to happen

00:35:29.620 --> 00:35:32.820
and what my career would be like.

00:35:33.060 --> 00:35:36.580
He knew that Luka
would be with me,

00:35:37.220 --> 00:35:40.220
that he would start playing
with me in Montpellier.

00:35:40.460 --> 00:35:44.380
Even though he didn’t live to see
our first results with the national team,

00:35:44.700 --> 00:35:47.740
he knew, a few months
before he passed away,

00:35:47.940 --> 00:35:50.820
that Luka would be
called up to the national team.

00:35:51.060 --> 00:35:54.660
So that means a lot to me.

00:35:55.060 --> 00:35:57.980
I know that he saw
it all in advance,

00:35:58.180 --> 00:36:01.940
and that now he’s watching
from somewhere.

00:36:03.300 --> 00:36:06.660
In the beginning,
it was really hard.

00:36:06.860 --> 00:36:11.780
Because when your father is your
role model, your coach, your agent,

00:36:12.180 --> 00:36:14.980
your motivation-everything-
and then he’s no longer there,

00:36:15.180 --> 00:36:18.220
you’re left without all of it.
You’re alone.

00:36:19.180 --> 00:36:26.900
I had to start making decisions
on my own and find my own path,

00:36:28.380 --> 00:36:31.220
both in sports and outside of it.

00:36:32.220 --> 00:36:36.740
It was really hard for me,
but now I’m happy,

00:36:37.300 --> 00:36:40.380
because I’m aware that
I wouldn’t be here without him.

00:36:40.620 --> 00:36:44.180
I focus more on the positive sides
than the negative ones.

00:36:44.420 --> 00:36:47.820
I know my father was always
a positive person, so I know

00:36:48.300 --> 00:36:51.580
he wouldn’t want us all to be sad
just because he’s no longer here.

00:36:52.180 --> 00:36:56.020
Yeah, but 56 years,
that’s really early.

00:36:57.900 --> 00:37:02.220
The number of trophies says a lot
about the greats and the leaders.

00:37:02.420 --> 00:37:05.300
I can see that from your story too.

00:37:05.540 --> 00:37:10.020
Those are the players
who have the most fame,

00:37:10.260 --> 00:37:14.340
and of course, the most attention.
They also have the best contracts,

00:37:15.140 --> 00:37:18.820
but at the same time, they take
on the greatest responsibility.

00:37:19.020 --> 00:37:23.460
You yourself said that before
every match, you feel nervous,

00:37:23.780 --> 00:37:26.540
because you know
the most is expected of you.

00:37:26.780 --> 00:37:29.620
That expectation comes from
the coach and the staff,

00:37:29.820 --> 00:37:34.220
your teammates, the media, the fans,
and in the end, from yourself.

00:37:34.460 --> 00:37:36.820
That sense of responsibility
is always there,

00:37:37.020 --> 00:37:38.940
that obligation: "I have to".

00:37:39.260 --> 00:37:46.900
I think you were right to notice that
the biggest pressure comes from me.

00:37:50.660 --> 00:37:57.380
Because that goal I had since I was a child
kept pulling me forward so strongly.

00:38:01.300 --> 00:38:06.580
I wanted to succeed so badly,
and I expected a lot from myself.

00:38:06.860 --> 00:38:10.380
I wanted to be the best,
and to always give everything I had.

00:38:10.620 --> 00:38:15.060
The fact that I wanted to be the best
might sound arrogant,

00:38:15.300 --> 00:38:20.700
but it was really something internal,
something that pushed me every day

00:38:21.060 --> 00:38:25.740
to give my all, on the court,
in training, and in life in general.

00:38:26.260 --> 00:38:30.220
And that, for me, was the greatest
source of pressure.

00:38:31.020 --> 00:38:34.980
Of course, it wasn’t easy
living with that, and I think

00:38:35.820 --> 00:38:39.740
all top athletes feel
that kind of pressure,

00:38:39.980 --> 00:38:42.518
which is even greater
than the pressure from

00:38:42.683 --> 00:38:49.690
15,000-20,000 people cheering,
shouting, or the media, and so on.

00:38:50.460 --> 00:38:55.540
The biggest pressure came from myself,
and it was always like that.

00:38:55.820 --> 00:39:00.220
Of course, it’s extremely stressful,
but I’m really proud

00:39:00.500 --> 00:39:03.460
that I managed to live a normal life.

00:39:05.580 --> 00:39:09.220
My father also insisted a lot
on the importance of knowing

00:39:09.900 --> 00:39:14.860
that in both sport and life, you have to
give 100% or even 200% for what you do.

00:39:15.180 --> 00:39:17.980
But you have to free yourself
from that pressure in order

00:39:18.220 --> 00:39:21.860
to live a normal life. That pressure
needs to stay on the court. -Bravo.

00:39:22.140 --> 00:39:25.700
So over the years,
I managed to get to a point

00:39:25.940 --> 00:39:30.340
where that pressure only exists
on match day. -You analyze...

00:39:30.900 --> 00:39:34.860
You have to know how to quickly
let it go, because in a way,

00:39:35.100 --> 00:39:38.740
there are two versions of you.

00:39:38.980 --> 00:39:42.420
You-and the one who
fights on the court,

00:39:43.140 --> 00:39:46.820
the one who would kill anyone
trying to beat me.

00:39:47.060 --> 00:39:50.420
You have to know how to deal
with it... -Which is hard.

00:39:50.660 --> 00:39:56.660
And you have to know
that you’re not the same.

00:39:57.340 --> 00:40:03.402
That’s always helped me
analyze myself as a player,

00:40:03.588 --> 00:40:08.006
and how I behave on the field,
but also adapt,

00:40:11.084 --> 00:40:13.389
because you're not the same player,

00:40:13.576 --> 00:40:15.789
nor the same person,
at 20 and at 40 years old.

00:40:16.006 --> 00:40:19.406
You have to find a new leader
and a new role

00:40:19.980 --> 00:40:26.425
within the team and on the court.
That also helped me.

00:40:27.380 --> 00:40:32.527
You said that, and it’s perfect,
it sounds super simple,

00:40:33.300 --> 00:40:36.420
but today it’s hard to let go of that,
especially because

00:40:36.660 --> 00:40:39.860
it doesn’t depend on you.
There are the media and the fans.

00:40:40.100 --> 00:40:43.940
Today, it’s hard for a player
to get out of that mindset.

00:40:44.140 --> 00:40:46.900
Yes. -It’s hard for him
to be without pressure.

00:40:47.021 --> 00:40:49.530
Because the pressure isn’t
only felt during the game.

00:40:49.853 --> 00:40:52.973
Social media creates constant pressure.

00:40:53.118 --> 00:40:55.311
You’re constantly under
a magnifying glass.

00:40:55.430 --> 00:40:57.811
The better the player you are,
the more intense it gets.

00:40:58.613 --> 00:41:02.493
That’s how it should be, because
you can’t completely free yourself from it,

00:41:02.640 --> 00:41:05.803
but you’ve already mentioned
several times

00:41:05.900 --> 00:41:08.180
that you work on yourself,
improve, and so on.

00:41:08.311 --> 00:41:10.751
Yes. What you said is true.

00:41:10.857 --> 00:41:15.330
Nowadays, social media
are also present.

00:41:16.300 --> 00:41:23.140
If you want, you can spend the whole day
on your phone, on Instagram,

00:41:23.540 --> 00:41:29.620
X, Facebook, TikTok. There’s also TV,
newspapers, podcasts.

00:41:30.260 --> 00:41:35.900
So basically, you can
feed your ego all day long.

00:41:36.100 --> 00:41:40.140
And if you don’t know how to step away
from it a bit and calm your ego,

00:41:40.420 --> 00:41:44.860
to realize that you are not just that,
it can be tough.

00:41:45.140 --> 00:41:50.300
Yes, that can consume you.
That your ego actually consumes you.

00:41:50.700 --> 00:41:56.460
I’ve worked a lot on that,
to learn how my ego works,

00:41:56.700 --> 00:42:01.300
how I can calm it,
how I can free myself from it.

00:42:02.020 --> 00:42:06.460
That’s also very interesting,
as we already mentioned.

00:42:07.380 --> 00:42:11.660
I always thought it was a shame
that as an athlete,

00:42:11.829 --> 00:42:17.011
I have to end my career by 40,
while a singer or an actor

00:42:17.269 --> 00:42:19.851
can do it their whole life.

00:42:21.140 --> 00:42:28.580
But at the same time, I’ve overcome that,
and that’s where my strength lies.

00:42:29.500 --> 00:42:34.860
Now I have to end my career
and find a new life.

00:42:35.100 --> 00:42:42.732
You have to live a normal life
and let go of that persona and ego.

00:42:43.765 --> 00:42:48.525
You have to understand all of that
and grow as a person, not just as a player.

00:42:49.380 --> 00:42:51.900
Yes, exactly.
-That’s also very important.

00:42:52.180 --> 00:42:59.060
We said that your club career
is incomparable to anyone else’s.

00:42:59.700 --> 00:43:02.940
You mentioned the Tricolores,
the national team...

00:43:03.500 --> 00:43:09.660
You’ve always emphasized that it’s
an honor and pride to play for France.

00:43:11.420 --> 00:43:14.780
So-three Olympic gold medals,
four World Championship golds,

00:43:15.180 --> 00:43:20.180
four European Championship golds,
we won’t count the silvers and bronzes.

00:43:22.780 --> 00:43:29.100
Here in Croatia, we used to call
matches against France El Clásico.

00:43:29.464 --> 00:43:37.488
Were we your biggest rivals?
Was it seen that way on your side as well?

00:43:38.325 --> 00:43:40.921
Yes, that’s recognized here too.

00:43:41.340 --> 00:43:53.404
That period between 2004-2005
up until maybe 2014,

00:43:53.860 --> 00:43:58.980
we always played against Croatia
in the final, semifinal, or quarterfinal.

00:43:59.460 --> 00:44:05.900
Those matches were always the hardest.
For France, of course, and for me.

00:44:07.820 --> 00:44:10.820
I can’t describe how I feel.

00:44:11.100 --> 00:44:14.780
I’m playing against Croatia,
and my father is from Croatia.

00:44:15.180 --> 00:44:19.060
My roots are Croatian,
and I’m very proud of that.

00:44:19.260 --> 00:44:24.980
When Croatia plays,
I cheer for Croatia.

00:44:25.260 --> 00:44:28.380
Just like I do for Serbia,
and all of our former countries,

00:44:28.580 --> 00:44:31.380
when they play handball or football.

00:44:32.580 --> 00:44:35.860
I saw you during Croatia–France
in 1998, the semifinal,

00:44:36.060 --> 00:44:38.620
and that was the toughest match for me.

00:44:38.860 --> 00:44:42.300
I celebrated when you scored.
Then I was sad afterwards.

00:44:42.540 --> 00:44:45.540
And if I play for France, I feel proud.

00:44:46.060 --> 00:44:49.620
And those matches were always
something very difficult.

00:44:49.860 --> 00:44:53.980
Of course, when we didn’t play
against Croatia, they all loved me.

00:44:54.220 --> 00:44:57.820
They’d take photos with me,
and they were always nice.

00:44:58.020 --> 00:45:01.820
But when we played Croatia,
they cursed my mom and dad.

00:45:03.140 --> 00:45:07.740
It got so tough that I had to work
on it mentally, to prepare well.

00:45:07.940 --> 00:45:12.900
And of course, those games
were always the hardest.

00:45:13.140 --> 00:45:19.336
I will always remember the final
in 2009, in Zagreb,

00:45:19.625 --> 00:45:28.937
when I saw how the fans welcomed me.
I saw my father in the stands.

00:45:29.099 --> 00:45:32.757
The anthem started playing,
and I almost cried,

00:45:32.899 --> 00:45:35.849
because I saw my father crying.

00:45:36.178 --> 00:45:40.026
And my mom crying too-
it’s hard to describe.

00:45:40.588 --> 00:45:47.701
But of course, I’m proud that
we won those matches more often.

00:45:48.009 --> 00:45:54.185
I’m proud to play for France,
because France wins titles.

00:45:54.729 --> 00:45:57.247
Thanks to the whole team,
but thanks to me too,

00:45:57.365 --> 00:45:59.569
because I’m one of the best players.

00:46:00.052 --> 00:46:05.037
France won thanks to ex-Yugoslavia.

00:46:07.380 --> 00:46:10.885
Maybe Luka and I wouldn’t be here.

00:46:11.129 --> 00:46:15.431
All of us, former Yugoslavians,
came to improve handball in France.

00:46:15.637 --> 00:46:18.517
If that hadn’t happened,
France wouldn’t be where it is.

00:46:18.860 --> 00:46:21.580
That motivated me.

00:46:21.820 --> 00:46:25.820
And of course, those matches
against Croatia were legendary.

00:46:26.060 --> 00:46:34.803
That team had: Balić, Džomba,
Rašković, Metličić, and others.

00:46:38.224 --> 00:46:41.146
You were there...
They called it "El Clasico".

00:46:41.560 --> 00:46:44.000
But France won more often.

00:46:44.460 --> 00:46:49.380
Where was the line
that made you better?

00:46:49.900 --> 00:46:54.740
I had coffee with Ivano lately-
he said hello to you.

00:46:55.220 --> 00:46:59.660
We often drink coffee
in the same café in Split.

00:47:00.020 --> 00:47:05.540
He said your team had quality
individuals and squad depth.

00:47:05.900 --> 00:47:12.209
That’s France. We were more about
energy, quality, and craziness,

00:47:12.826 --> 00:47:17.779
intensity, togetherness, and all that.

00:47:19.620 --> 00:47:22.500
How did you see France’s advantage?

00:47:25.020 --> 00:47:32.100
Croatia-strangely, I was talking
about it 2-3 days ago,

00:47:33.900 --> 00:47:37.740
with the author writing a book.

00:47:38.420 --> 00:47:41.620
In 2003, Croatia won
the World Championship,

00:47:41.900 --> 00:47:48.540
in a match that maybe sparked
the rivalry with France.

00:47:49.100 --> 00:47:55.420
Croatia lost to Argentina in Portugal,
and France was the favorite.

00:47:56.460 --> 00:47:59.180
We lost to Croatia then.

00:47:59.460 --> 00:48:04.140
That was the start of that generation:
Ivano, Rašković, and the rest.

00:48:05.140 --> 00:48:11.580
We launched them, and it gave
them a lot of confidence.

00:48:13.540 --> 00:48:19.913
In 2003, they were world champs.
In 2004, they won the Olympics.

00:48:21.260 --> 00:48:27.220
In 2005, they beat us 2-5 in the semis
of the World Championship in Tunisia.

00:48:27.407 --> 00:48:29.767
They had the edge.

00:48:29.951 --> 00:48:34.525
We slowly built our team.

00:48:35.340 --> 00:48:40.260
I was still young then-
I learned a lot in Germany.

00:48:41.100 --> 00:48:48.700
All those individual players
went to top clubs.

00:48:49.980 --> 00:48:54.340
Omeyer went to the Bundesliga.
I went to Kiel with Noka.

00:48:54.860 --> 00:48:59.244
Everything I learned I brought
into the national team.

00:48:59.503 --> 00:49:03.283
Narcisse went to Germany too,
Abalo to Ciudad Real,

00:49:03.511 --> 00:49:08.040
Dinart to Ciudad Real to learn
from Dujshebaev and his talent.

00:49:08.267 --> 00:49:11.827
And all he learned he brought
back to the national team.

00:49:12.083 --> 00:49:17.843
We all went abroad and got a lot.
We were strong, mentally and physically.

00:49:18.061 --> 00:49:23.741
We went to learn handball from
other coaches in other countries.

00:49:23.975 --> 00:49:27.657
We brought all that experience
into the French team.

00:49:27.955 --> 00:49:33.229
It also helped in 2007,
when we lost in Germany,

00:49:33.403 --> 00:49:37.254
in the World Championship
semifinal, after extra time.

00:49:37.520 --> 00:49:41.040
In the end, bad calls from refs-
it really upset us.

00:49:41.820 --> 00:49:48.058
That was a turning point, because
after that loss, we won everything.

00:49:48.620 --> 00:49:54.020
That defeat hit us so hard,
we said, "never again".

00:49:54.940 --> 00:50:01.780
That’s when the killer instinct
in the team was born.

00:50:05.500 --> 00:50:11.501
Would you say France’s rise
paralleled your own rise?

00:50:11.846 --> 00:50:14.782
You said you were still
young in 2003? -Yes.

00:50:15.159 --> 00:50:18.039
You were at the tournament,
but didn’t play? -Yes.

00:50:19.500 --> 00:50:26.613
And you became the key piece,
the missing link for France.

00:50:27.380 --> 00:50:37.260
Now looking at it as a player,
from this region,

00:50:40.020 --> 00:50:44.580
Croatia, Slovenia, Montenegro,
North Macedonia, BiH, Serbia.

00:50:44.940 --> 00:50:48.220
Is Croatia still the best?

00:50:51.860 --> 00:50:56.820
Why? Is it talent, mentality,
dedication, or a mix of all that?

00:50:57.140 --> 00:50:59.180
What sets us apart?

00:50:59.460 --> 00:51:03.260
First, of course, mentality.

00:51:03.620 --> 00:51:13.498
As you said-fire, and role models
young Croatians had growing up.

00:51:14.540 --> 00:51:21.060
There was Ivano, Petar, Blaž,
Džomba, all those stars.

00:51:22.700 --> 00:51:29.318
You can’t measure the impact
they had on the youth.

00:51:29.580 --> 00:51:35.365
When you see someone succeed
from your country,

00:51:36.380 --> 00:51:42.529
it tells you that you can too,
if you give it your all.

00:51:44.734 --> 00:51:50.236
And of course, that old Balkan system

00:51:50.656 --> 00:51:55.976
where kids constantly train sports
at school-handball, basketball...

00:51:56.146 --> 00:51:59.165
It helps you grow. It shapes
your technique and tactics.

00:51:59.284 --> 00:52:01.619
That’s something we lack in France.

00:52:01.760 --> 00:52:07.520
Maybe two hours of sport
per week, four at most.

00:52:07.649 --> 00:52:15.901
In school and college,
that’s a big advantage.

00:52:17.870 --> 00:52:24.323
And of course, the role models
young Croats grew up with,

00:52:25.723 --> 00:52:30.237
plus their strong technique
and deep tactical training.

00:52:30.540 --> 00:52:36.180
Coaches from former Yugoslavia
have something France doesn’t.

00:52:36.402 --> 00:52:39.242
That’s a big advantage too.

00:52:40.013 --> 00:52:42.737
Of course, the domestic
league isn’t strong.

00:52:42.963 --> 00:52:48.187
All the best players leave
to live off the sport. -Yes.

00:52:48.681 --> 00:52:54.585
They grow like I did. With Noka,
I had a different path.

00:52:54.773 --> 00:53:01.053
I didn’t go through Balkan school,
but I spent time with my father.

00:53:01.482 --> 00:53:06.682
We spent lots of time at home,
playing-not just handball…

00:53:06.868 --> 00:53:09.988
We played basketball and football.
I also learned tennis.

00:53:10.156 --> 00:53:12.276
And he always told me:

00:53:12.463 --> 00:53:16.559
The most important thing is
coordination of body and head.

00:53:16.683 --> 00:53:19.786
That’s how I learned,
with my dad.

00:53:21.140 --> 00:53:26.860
I learned what the French did well:
physical training.

00:53:29.020 --> 00:53:33.900
In France, we worked hard
on physical strength.

00:53:34.300 --> 00:53:37.100
We spent a lot of time in the gym,
focused on fitness.

00:53:37.340 --> 00:53:42.020
That gave us a huge edge
over other countries,

00:53:42.300 --> 00:53:45.660
when you had guys like Dinart,
he was a machine.

00:53:45.900 --> 00:53:50.300
Bertrand Gille, Narcisse,
they were pure athletes.

00:53:50.500 --> 00:53:55.740
And then, the technique and tactics
I learned from Noka,

00:53:55.980 --> 00:53:58.380
who taught me everything
about positioning and tactics,

00:53:58.660 --> 00:54:03.060
and how to view the game differently.

00:54:03.340 --> 00:54:06.660
That made a huge difference.

00:54:06.900 --> 00:54:11.340
Everything I learned from Noka,
I brought into the national team.

00:54:11.540 --> 00:54:15.380
Onesta realized we knew
more than he did.

00:54:15.660 --> 00:54:18.780
And he let us take charge.

00:54:19.020 --> 00:54:25.060
All those combinations helped us
dominate international handball.

00:54:27.740 --> 00:54:32.140
That drive and energy,
as people say,

00:54:32.460 --> 00:54:38.140
it influences everything in this region,
especially handball.

00:54:38.420 --> 00:54:42.620
Same with other countries.

00:54:44.420 --> 00:54:48.660
The Serbs are great at basketball.
We’re strong in football now.

00:54:48.860 --> 00:54:50.820
Because you need quality.

00:54:51.060 --> 00:54:58.780
You mentioned Čavar, then later Ivano
Balić, Džomba and Duvnjak...

00:54:59.580 --> 00:55:05.540
You need elite talent
to build mentality around.

00:55:05.740 --> 00:55:09.900
That’s all built on top of that.
Just like we have Modrić in football.

00:55:10.100 --> 00:55:13.340
And that’s why we’re here,
and not some other country.

00:55:13.580 --> 00:55:19.980
You must have at least one
genius to build around.

00:55:20.340 --> 00:55:23.380
For us, it was Ivano, right?

00:55:24.784 --> 00:55:28.104
He’s five years older than you?

00:55:28.477 --> 00:55:36.202
That’s a lot, but still close.
Was he special?

00:55:36.459 --> 00:55:39.534
Do you remember the rivalry?

00:55:40.500 --> 00:55:46.700
That iconic photo from 2009,
some called it a "dethroning".

00:55:48.060 --> 00:55:51.340
The old lion leaves,
the young lion steps in.

00:55:52.900 --> 00:55:58.020
Ivano was one of the best
handball players of all time.

00:55:59.220 --> 00:56:04.260
He’s a legend, and yet we never
played on the same team.

00:56:04.500 --> 00:56:08.780
We were always opponents.
He was in Pamplona, I was in Kiel.

00:56:09.060 --> 00:56:12.380
We faced off in the Champions
League semifinal,

00:56:12.580 --> 00:56:16.660
then Croatia vs France.
Like you said, a huge rivalry.

00:56:17.860 --> 00:56:24.500
I remember, we were playing
and the score was 2:9.

00:56:24.900 --> 00:56:31.296
The media focused only
on the Croatia-France final.

00:56:33.468 --> 00:56:41.039
I read headlines in papers
where they quoted me,

00:56:41.320 --> 00:56:46.265
saying things about Ivano
I never actually said.

00:56:46.416 --> 00:56:49.296
It’s crazy how things get twisted.

00:56:49.780 --> 00:56:56.140
I had huge respect for him.
All that was out of our control.

00:56:56.740 --> 00:57:05.500
It was all edited like that.
But as a player, of course,

00:57:05.740 --> 00:57:10.780
I wanted to be better than Ivano,
because any athlete’s goal

00:57:11.060 --> 00:57:15.060
is to compete and be better
than the rest-and the best.

00:57:15.300 --> 00:57:22.300
Still, I admired the way he played.
And I admired how Croatia played,

00:57:22.940 --> 00:57:30.980
even though they were our rivals.
I knew-if we, as a team,

00:57:31.220 --> 00:57:37.740
and me as a player, wanted to be
the best, we had to beat them.

00:57:37.894 --> 00:57:40.294
We had to be better than Croatia.

00:57:40.496 --> 00:57:46.456
I was always in that paradox
of respect and rivalry.

00:57:46.663 --> 00:57:49.940
Because I had to be better than him.

00:57:51.221 --> 00:57:54.984
Sadly, we never played
on the same team.

00:57:55.350 --> 00:58:04.348
Maybe once-some charity match.
But I always respected Ivano

00:58:04.544 --> 00:58:06.747
and that entire great generation.

00:58:11.740 --> 00:58:13.540
That’s all for this episode.

00:58:13.649 --> 00:58:16.849
Watch part two of the interview
with N. Karabatić in the next episode.

